class="post-210493 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-climate-environment category-csr-3p tag-china tag-great-pacific-garbage-patch tag-litter tag-ocean-plastic tag-ocean-waste tag-recycling tag-waste" id="post-210493"><h2><a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/china-leads-plastic-donations-pacific-garbage-patch/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to China Leads in Contributions to Pacific Garbage Patch"><span
itemprop="name">China Leads in Contributions to Pacific Garbage Patch</span></a></h2><div
class="meta"><div
class="authorImg"> <img
alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0ef4b8fb96b237a285e9b7fdc32ff11e?s=18&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D18&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-18 photo' height='18' width='18' /></div><div
class="authorInfo"><h5><a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/author/bob-siegel/" title="Visit RP Siegel&#8217;s website" rel="author external">RP Siegel</a> |  Thursday February 19th, 2015 | <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/china-leads-plastic-donations-pacific-garbage-patch/#comments" title="Comments on China Leads in Contributions to Pacific Garbage Patch"><span
class="dsq-postid" data-dsqidentifier="210493 http://www.triplepundit.com/?p=210493">0 Comments</span></a></h5></div></div><div
class="entry"><div
class="bottomcontainerBox" style="border:1px solid #808080;background-color:#F0F4F9;"><div
style="float:left; width:85px;padding-right:10px; margin:4px 4px 4px 4px;height:30px;"> <iframe
src="http://www.facebook.com/plugins/like.php?href=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.triplepundit.com%2F2015%2F02%2Fchina-leads-plastic-donations-pacific-garbage-patch%2F&amp;layout=button_count&amp;show_faces=false&amp;width=85&amp;action=like&amp;font=verdana&amp;colorscheme=light&amp;height=21" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" style="border:none; overflow:hidden; width=85px; height:21px;" allowTransparency="true"></iframe></div><div
style="float:left; width:80px;padding-right:10px; margin:4px 4px 4px 4px;height:30px;"> <g:plusone size="medium" href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/china-leads-plastic-donations-pacific-garbage-patch/"></g:plusone></div><div
style="float:left; width:95px;padding-right:10px; margin:4px 4px 4px 4px;height:30px;"> <a
href="http://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-url="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/china-leads-plastic-donations-pacific-garbage-patch/"  data-text="China Leads in Contributions to Pacific Garbage Patch" data-count="horizontal" data-via="triplepundit">Tweet</a></div><div
style="float:left; width:105px;padding-right:10px; margin:4px 4px 4px 4px;height:30px;"><script type="in/share" data-url="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/china-leads-plastic-donations-pacific-garbage-patch/" data-counter="right"></script></div></div><div
style="clear:both"></div><div
style="padding-bottom:4px;"></div><p><img
class="alignright size-medium wp-image-210495" src="http://cdn7.triplepundit.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/garbage-patch-map-300x200.jpg" alt="garbage patch map" width="300" height="200" />We’ve all heard a lot about plastic pollution, which has led to a movement away from plastic shopping bags and bottled water in the U.S. A principal driver of these actions has been a growing awareness of the so-called “<a
href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3JXWRVrFiKs#t=142">Great Pacific Garbage Patch</a>,” a floating island of plastic twice the size of Texas. This unplanned floating dump, also known as the Pacific Trash Vortex, comes about because of swirling ocean currents known as the <a
href="http://education.nationalgeographic.com/education/encyclopedia/great-pacific-garbage-patch/?ar_a=1">North Pacific Subtropical Gyre</a>. The full extent of the patch stretches from just off the U.S. West Coast to the East Coast of Japan.</p><p>A recent study in <a
href="http://www.sciencemag.org/content/347/6223/768">Science</a> analyzed the contents of the patch. The study determined that in 2010 there were 275 million metric tons of trash found in the patch. The <a
href="http://grist.org/living/theres-a-scary-amount-of-plastic-in-the-ocean-heres-who-put-it-there/?utm_source=syndication&amp;utm_medium=rss&amp;utm_campaign=feed">team</a>, led by Jenna Jambeck from the University of Georgia, estimated that an additional 4.8 million to 12.7 million metric tons were being added to the patch each year. So, the question is: Where is all that trash coming from?</p> <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/china-leads-plastic-donations-pacific-garbage-patch/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to China Leads in Contributions to Pacific Garbage Patch"> Click to continue reading &raquo;</a><p
class="more"><img
src="http://www.triplepundit.com/wp-content/themes/triplepunditv2/images/page_white_text.png"  alt="Permalink" /> <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/china-leads-plastic-donations-pacific-garbage-patch/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to China Leads in Contributions to Pacific Garbage Patch"> CONTINUES &raquo;</a> <img
alt="discuss" src="http://www.triplepundit.com/wp-content/themes/triplepunditv2/images/usergroup2-vi.gif" /> <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/china-leads-plastic-donations-pacific-garbage-patch/">Discuss This &raquo;</a></p></div></div><div
class="post-210331 post type-post status-publish format-standard has-post-thumbnail hentry category-clean-tech tag-eco-tourism-ecuador tag-energy-efficiency tag-heat-recovery tag-heat-recovery-ventilation" id="post-210331"><h2><a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/energy-efficient-vs-traditional-4-strategies-building-efficient-home/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to 4 Strategies for Building an Efficient Home"><span
itemprop="name">4 Strategies for Building an Efficient Home</span></a></h2><div
class="meta"><div
class="authorImg"> <img
alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/0610cc9b07f8377afc956726e94343c9?s=18&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D18&amp;r=PG' class='avatar avatar-18 photo' height='18' width='18' /></div><div
class="authorInfo"><h5><a
href="http://www.SarahLozanova.com" title="Visit Sarah Lozanova&#8217;s website" rel="author external">Sarah Lozanova</a> |  Thursday February 19th, 2015 | <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/energy-efficient-vs-traditional-4-strategies-building-efficient-home/#comments" title="Comments on 4 Strategies for Building an Efficient Home"><span
class="dsq-postid" data-dsqidentifier="210331 http://www.triplepundit.com/?p=210331">0 Comments</span></a></h5></div></div><div
class="entry"><div
class="bottomcontainerBox" style="border:1px solid #808080;background-color:#F0F4F9;"><div
style="float:left; width:85px;padding-right:10px; margin:4px 4px 4px 4px;height:30px;"> <iframe
src="http://www.facebook.com/plugins/like.php?href=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.triplepundit.com%2F2015%2F02%2Fenergy-efficient-vs-traditional-4-strategies-building-efficient-home%2F&amp;layout=button_count&amp;show_faces=false&amp;width=85&amp;action=like&amp;font=verdana&amp;colorscheme=light&amp;height=21" scrolling="no" frameborder="0" style="border:none; overflow:hidden; width=85px; height:21px;" allowTransparency="true"></iframe></div><div
style="float:left; width:80px;padding-right:10px; margin:4px 4px 4px 4px;height:30px;"> <g:plusone size="medium" href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/energy-efficient-vs-traditional-4-strategies-building-efficient-home/"></g:plusone></div><div
style="float:left; width:95px;padding-right:10px; margin:4px 4px 4px 4px;height:30px;"> <a
href="http://twitter.com/share" class="twitter-share-button" data-url="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/energy-efficient-vs-traditional-4-strategies-building-efficient-home/"  data-text="4 Strategies for Building an Efficient Home" data-count="horizontal" data-via="triplepundit">Tweet</a></div><div
style="float:left; width:105px;padding-right:10px; margin:4px 4px 4px 4px;height:30px;"><script type="in/share" data-url="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/energy-efficient-vs-traditional-4-strategies-building-efficient-home/" data-counter="right"></script></div></div><div
style="clear:both"></div><div
style="padding-bottom:4px;"></div><div
style="text-align: right; text-size: .9em;"><a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/topic/eco-tourism-ecuador"><img
class="aligncenter size-large wp-image-202381" src="http://cdn6.triplepundit.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/eco-tourism-3p-650x75.gif" alt="eco-tourism-3p" width="650" height="75" />Read more in this series</a></div><p><img
class="alignright size-medium wp-image-210337" src="http://cdn8.triplepundit.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/winter-comfort-zehnder-300x199.jpg" alt="belfast ecovillage" width="300" height="199" />I&#8217;m visiting  <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/topic/eco-tourism-ecuador/" target="_blank">Ecuador</a> at the moment, and I&#8217;ve been struck by the fact that most of the homes on the coast and in Quito have no heating or air conditioning systems. Straddling the equator, much of the country has a relatively mild climate, with a wet and dry season. This allows many people to have a small energy footprint. Relying on ventilation from windows and doors alone, homes are relatively comfortable throughout the year. This is not the case in the United States, where most people heat or cool their homes much of the year.</p><p>Back in Midcoast Maine, we live in a high performance house in <a
href="mainecohousing.org" target="_blank">Belfast Ecovillage</a>, a 36-unit community built to the <a
href="http://www.greenbuildermedia.com/blog/community-of-passive-homes-becomes-reality-in-maine" target="_blank">Passive House standard</a> (but not certified). While neighbors in our cold climate pay thousands of dollars to heat their homes, we pay just a couple hundred. Our home has generous amounts of insulation, triple-pane windows and doors, and is air sealed, so little heated air escapes to the outside. Because the home is nearly airtight, we have a <a
href="zehnderamerica.com" target="_blank">Zehnder heat recovery ventilation system</a> to continuously bring fresh air into the home, while recycling the heat from the exhaust air.  Numerous qualities set high performance homes apart from their code-built counterparts.</p> <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/energy-efficient-vs-traditional-4-strategies-building-efficient-home/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to 4 Strategies for Building an Efficient Home"> Click to continue reading &raquo;</a><p
class="more"><img
src="http://www.triplepundit.com/wp-content/themes/triplepunditv2/images/page_white_text.png"  alt="Permalink" /> <a
