style="clear:both"></div><div
style="padding-bottom:4px;"></div><div
id="attachment_210442" style="width: 310px" class="wp-caption alignright"><img
class="size-medium wp-image-210442" src="http://cdn6.triplepundit.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/548A8652-300x189.jpg" alt="Hayunan Wangse flys a kite with a fishing lure that mimics a flying fish on the surface , 11th July 2014, Waepure, Buru Isand, Indonesia.  He hopes 'Fair Trade' will bring improvements to his village. " width="300" height="189" /><p
class="wp-caption-text">Hayunan Wangse flys a kite with a fishing lure, which mimics a flying fish on the surface, on July 11, 2014 in Waepure, Buru Island, Indonesia. He hopes &#8216;Fair Trade&#8217; will bring improvements to his village.</p></div><p>Look out Whole Foods: <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/topic/safeway/" target="_blank">Safeway</a> is pulling ahead when it comes to <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2014/04/making-business-case-seafood-traceability/" target="_blank">seafood transparency</a>.</p><p><a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/topic/whole-foods/" target="_blank">Whole Foods</a> met its match when Safeway was ranked <a
href="http://www.fastcoexist.com/1679901/how-safeway-became-the-best-supermarket-for-sustainable-seafood">slightly ahead for seafood sustainability by Greenpeace back in 2011</a>. Both retailers had much to celebrate when they came out with the NGO&#8217;s first ever seafood rating of &#8220;good.&#8221;</p><p>Safeway hasn&#8217;t taken its foot off the gas pedal in recent years, though. The company has continued to push ahead <a
href="http://fishwise.org/safeway">toward an audacious goal of 100 percent sustainable sourcing for all fresh and frozen seafood</a> by the end of this year. The grocer&#8217;s latest commitment brings it up to par with your local farmers market when it comes to worker transparency.</p><p>Sustainable seafood awareness and availability have moved in leaps and bounds thanks to the hard work of organizations like <a
href="http://www.msc.org/">Marine Stewardship Council</a>, <a
href="http://www.montereybayaquarium.org/">Monterey Bay Aquarium</a> and <a
href="http://www.futureoffish.org/">Future of Fish</a>. These organizations work simultaneously on consumer education and seafood supply issues to ensure that when consumers set out to make a responsible purchase, they find good product availability on the shelves. But much of that seafood advocacy work has focused on environmental issues. Social issues &#8212; from forced labor and child labor to a lack of workplace safety precautions &#8212; remain a huge area of concern worldwide. Which is why the latest partnership between <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/topic/future-of-fair-trade/" target="_blank">Fair Trade USA</a> and Safeway is so exciting.</p> <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/seafood-now-fair-trade-certified/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Your Seafood: Now Fair Trade Certified"> Click to continue reading &raquo;</a><p
class="more"><img
src="http://www.triplepundit.com/wp-content/themes/triplepunditv2/images/page_white_text.png"  alt="Permalink" /> <a
href="http://www.triplepundit.com/2015/02/seafood-now-fair-trade-certified/" rel="bookmark" title="Permanent Link to Your Seafood: Now Fair Trade Certified"> CONTINUES &raquo;</a> <img
